41:20.156 --> 41:23.921
What's the best piece of work you've done in 
astronomy? The best piece of work I've done is

41:23.941 --> 41:35.357
probably the work on the spectrum of Neptune's 
satellite, Triton, in which persistence in

41:36.316 --> 41:58.250
Studying the near-infrared spectrum produced 
the detection and identification of methane,

41:36.316 --> 41:58.250
frozen methane on Triton, and frozen nitrogen, 
which we now recognize as the dominant material on

41:36.316 --> 41:58.250
the surface of Triton and Pluto. I continue to 
pursue this as the technology permits us to do a

41:59.632 --> 42:04.720
better and better job. Now, in 1989, of course, 
Voyager flew by Triton and found some very

42:05.392 --> 42:17.750
interesting things and corroborated the 
presence of nitrogen and methane, but it didn't

42:05.392 --> 42:17.750
show anything else. And in the meantime, we've 
found from additional ground-based work, carbon

42:18.030 --> 42:30.449
dioxide and carbon monoxide ices on Triton, and 
evidence of some other very interesting

42:18.030 --> 42:30.449
hydrocarbons, which we haven't even yet 
announced. So it turns out that the persistence in

42:31.911 --> 42:34.875
trying to detect, measure, and interpret the 
spectrum of a little object, 30 astronomical

42:35.463 --> 43:04.558
units from the sun, something that has a 
temperature in the neighborhood of less than 40

42:35.463 --> 43:04.558
Kelvin and is to the telescope only almost 14th 
magnitude, has proven to be a very, very rich

42:35.463 --> 43:04.558
spectrum, which we continue to interpret and find 
extremely interesting chemistry and

42:35.463 --> 43:04.558
information on the early development of the solar 
system. What did you have the most fun doing so far?

43:08.410 --> 43:11.893
Well, certainly the work on nitrogen has been some 
of the most fun. I also had an enormous amount of fun

43:13.134 --> 43:20.861
with our 20-micron detections of faint objects in 
the solar system. And I remember very well

43:21.602 --> 43:34.393
standing on the Cassegrain platform in the cold at 
the 88-inch telescope in Hawaii in the mid-'70s,

43:21.602 --> 43:34.393
measuring the thermal radiation from Trojan 
asteroids at 20 microns. These are objects which

43:36.025 --> 43:39.971
had never been detected thermally before. And I 
was able to get the first measurements of heat from

43:40.933 --> 43:48.425
those dark, small, little objects. And by the way, 
the detection of heat itself indicated that they

43:48.906 --> 43:56.538
were dark objects which absorbed a lot of sunlight 
and had low albedos. Similarly, with two of the

43:56.558 --> 44:01.225
outer satellites of Jupiter, I knew what I was 
looking for. I knew that if I could detect them at

44:01.508 --> 44:05.212
all, that that meant they were little black 
objects. And standing there on the platform

44:05.873 --> 44:13.923
seeing the strip chart recorder make a positive 
detection was a tremendous thrill. Have you had

44:15.164 --> 44:17.106
any fiascos or dead ends? Oh, sure. I've had some 
mistakes. What's your greatest fiasco? Well, I'd

44:20.631 --> 44:28.680
preface this by saying that I've enjoyed being on 
what is a cutting edge. of detections and

44:29.065 --> 44:32.989
measurements in planetary astronomy. And when 
you're on an edge, you can fall sometimes on one

44:33.770 --> 44:38.876
side and fall sometimes on the other. I've already 
told you about the successes in which I fell on the

44:39.437 --> 44:44.262
right side of the edge. There have been a couple of 
failures where I've fallen on the other side.

44:48.247 --> 44:57.317
Probably the worst one was the apparent detection 
of helium emission in the spectrum of Io,

44:48.247 --> 44:57.317
Jupiter's satellite Io. We in Hawaii, one of the 
first things I did there was to work on a

44:58.276 --> 45:05.066
near-infrared Fourier transform spectrometer. 
And one of the first things we looked at with this

45:05.967 --> 45:18.746
spectrometer after we finally got it online with 
the 88-inch telescope was IO, by which time sodium

45:05.967 --> 45:18.746
emission had already been detected in the 
spectrum by Robert Brown and colleagues. But we

45:19.407 --> 45:21.150
looked at it, and we detected this. We, that is with 
Carl Pilcher and Bill Sinton, we detected helium

45:21.310 --> 45:28.080
emission, the 10-8-30 band or line of helium. We 
rushed to a meeting that was held in Ithaca and

45:28.617 --> 45:35.102
reported this and sent out an IAU circular on it. 
And Don Hunton congratulated us on the detection

45:35.663 --> 45:39.726
of helium emission. No one understood what it 
meant, but they were all willing to believe that

45:39.786 --> 45:46.012
this very peculiar object had helium emission. 
